863→K22x16\n   864→16\n   865→K25x16\n   866→16\n   867→K30x20\n   868→20\n   869→K35x30\n   870→30\n   871→하드웨어 사양\n   872→81\n   873→\n   874→\n   875→=== 페이지 82 ===\n   876→Screw Size\n   877→Depth\n   878→K40x30\n   879→30\n   880→K50x30\n   881→30\n   882→Example of WN 1411 in NYLON PA Type 6\n   883→Screw Size\n   884→Depth\n   885→K18x10\n   886→10\n   887→K20x10\n   888→10\n   889→K22x16\n   890→16\n   891→K25x16\n   892→16\n   893→K30x20\n   894→20\n   895→K35x30\n   896→30\n   897→K40x30\n   898→30\n   899→K50x30\n   900→30\n   901→Example of DIN 7500 M in Aluminium EN AW-5754\n   902→Screw Size\n   903→Depth\n   904→M2x12\n   905→12\n   906→M2.5x20\n   907→20\n   908→M3x30\n   909→25\n   910→M4x30\n   911→30\n   912→M5x30\n   913→30\n   914→M6x30\n   915→11\n   916→There are three potential outcomes when testing a self-tapping screw:\n   917→1. The screw goes all the way in and is tightened with the set target torque. This is\n   918→successful operation.\n   919→2. The screw breaks while screwing in and the Screwdriver returns a result code / runtime\n   920→error: 10 - “Torque dropped unexpectedly”. This means that the screw cannot handle\n   921→such high torque on a material that hard.\n   922→하드웨어 사양\n   923→82\n   924→\n   925→\n   926→=== 페이지 83 ===\n   927→3. The Screwdriver stops halfway through and returns a result code / runtime error: 4 -\n   928→“Torque exceeded prematurely”. This means that a higher torque is needed to go through\n   929→that material with that screw. A solution could be to set a higher tightening torque.\n   930→For a successful tapping, ensure that the hole is made according to the screw manufacturer\n   931→specifications.\n   932→Torque accuracy Metric\n   933→Torque accuracy US Standard\n   934→하드웨어 사양\n   935→83\n   936→\n   937→\n   938→=== 페이지 84 ===\n   939→Screw-bit System\n   940→This system will highly increase the efficacy of the screws to be picked up, aligned with the\n   941→bit, moved around with the Screwdriver and screwed in/out. Therefore, it is highly\n   942→recommended to set up the Screw-bit System correctly to keep a high success rate.\n   943→Example of the Screw-bit System for an ISO 14579, M2 screw.\n   944→1 - Screw\n   945→2 - Screw fix\n   946→3 - Screw carrier\n   947→4 - Bit\n   948→5 - Bit holder\n   949→The following sections explain the different components of the Screw-bit System and how to\n   950→set it up correctly.\n   951→Screws\n   952→The first step is to know what type of screw is going to be used. The screw type will define\n   953→what type of screw fix (in any), screw carrier, bit, and bit holder shall be used.\n   954→참고\n   955→Use a chamfer for better reliability when making the screw hole.\n   956→The recommended screw types for the Screwdriver are the ones that have the properties\n   957→mentioned previously in the Supported Screws tables.\n   958→Screw Fix and Screw Carrier\n   959→Select the right screw fix and screw carrier depending on the screw type and the size to\n   960→maximize the efficacy of the Screw-bit System based on the table in section:\n   961→하드웨어 사양\n   962→84\n   963→\n   964→\n   965→=== 페이지 85 ===\n   966→•\n   967→Metric Screws\n   968→•\n   969→US Standard Screws\n   970→•\n   971→Self-tapping Screws for Aluminium\n   972→•\n   973→Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n   974→The screw fixes are needed for the DIN 912, ISO 4762, ISO 14579, ISO 14580, DIN 7981C /\n   975→ISO 7049, DIN 7981F / ISO 7049, WN 5251, WN 1411, WN 5451 and ASME B18.3 HEX\n   976→Cylinder screw types. The screw fixes have signifiers to show what size of screw they\n   977→support.\n   978→Screw fixes for Metric - DIN 912, ISO 4762, ISO 14579, ISO 14580, DIN 7981C / ISO 7049,\n   979→DIN 7981F / ISO 7049, WN 5251, WN 1411, WN 5451\n   980→M1.6\n   981→M2\n   982→M2.5\n   983→M3\n   984→M4\n   985→M5\n   986→M6\n   987→Screw fixes for US Standard - ASME B18.3 HEX Cylinder, DIN 7981C / ISO 7049, DIN\n   988→7981F / ISO 7049, WN 5251, WN 5451\n   989→1#\n   990→2#\n   991→4#\n   992→6#\n   993→8#\n   994→10#\n   995→1/4\"\n   996→The screw carriers also have signifiers to help identifying what screw type and size they can\n   997→be used with.\n   998→Screw thread size\n   999→Screw type illustration\n  1000→Bits\n  1001→Select the right bit depending on the screw type and size to maximize the efficacy of the\n  1002→Screw-bit System based on the table in section:\n  1003→•\n  1004→Metric Screws\n  1005→•\n  1006→US Standard Screws\n  1007→•\n  1008→Self-tapping Screws for Aluminium\n  1009→•\n  1010→Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n  1011→하드웨어 사양\n  1012→85\n  1013→\n  1014→\n  1015→=== 페이지 86 ===\n  1016→The bits have signifiers to help identifying what bit type and size they are.\n  1017→Screw type standard\n  1018→Shows bit size and type\n  1019→Din 912 / ISO 4762\n  1020→ASME B18.3 HEX Cylinder\n  1021→ISO 14579\n  1022→ISO 14580\n  1023→ISO 14581\n  1024→DIN 7500 M\n  1025→DIN 14586 C\n  1026→WN 5251\n  1027→ISO 4042\n  1028→WN 5451\n  1029→ASME B18.6.3 Torx Button head\n  1030→ASME B18.6.3 Torx Counter sunk\n  1031→DIN 7985A\n  1032→DIN 7981C / ISO 7049\n  1033→DIN 7981F / ISO 7049\n  1034→DIN 7982 C\n  1035→DIN 7983 C\n  1036→WN 1411\n  1037→ASME B18.6.3 Cross recessed Button head\n  1038→Supported bit shank properties:\n  1039→•\n  1040→Type 1/4\" HEX\n  1041→•\n  1042→Length 25 mm\n  1043→참고\n  1044→Bits longer than 25 mm could be used. However, the screw carrier and the\n  1045→screw fix might not hold the screw properly in place.\n  1046→Bit Holder\n  1047→Select the right bit holder depending on the screw type and size to maximize the efficacy of\n  1048→the Screw-bit System based on the table in section:\n  1049→•\n  1050→Metric Screws\n  1051→•\n  1052→US Standard Screws\n  1053→•\n  1054→Self-tapping Screws for Aluminium\n  1055→•\n  1056→Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n  1057→The bit holder generates a magnetic force that will keep the screw attached and aligned to\n  1058→the bit.\n  1059→There are two types of bit holders:\n  1060→하드웨어 사양\n  1061→86\n  1062→\n  1063→\n  1064→=== 페이지 87 ===\n  1065→•\n  1066→Bit Holder A: Generates a higher magnetic force. It is commonly used for the bigger and\n  1067→heavier screws.\n  1068→•\n  1069→Bit Holder B: Generates a lower magnetic force. It is commonly used for the smaller and\n  1070→lighter screws.\n  1071→경고\n  1072→If Bit Holder A is used for smaller and lighter screws instead of Bit Holder B,\n  1073→the screws can jump from the Screw Feeder to the Screwdriver because of\n  1074→the higher magnetic force.\n  1075→Bit Extenders 50 and 100 mm\n  1076→The bit extenders are a long version of the previously described bit holders. Bit extenders\n  1077→are useful to reach narrow spaces.\n  1078→The bit extenders have a lock nut to tighten against the screw carrier to ensure that the\n  1079→screw carrier does not move out of position over time.\n  1080→When the bit extenders are mounted on the Screwdriver, the maximum total radial runout\n  1081→can be up to 0.5 mm (measured below the thread as shown in the following picture).\n  1082→The bit extenders need to be purchased separately by contacting your vendor where the\n  1083→Screwdriver was purchased.\n  1084→•\n  1085→Bit extender type A 50 mm - PN 109301\n  1086→•\n  1087→Bit extender type B 50 mm - PN 109289\n  1088→•\n  1089→Bit extender type A 100 mm - PN 109290\n  1090→•\n  1091→Bit extender type B 100 mm - PN 109298\n  1092→For more information on the mechanical dimensions, go to the 7.2.2.1. Mechanical\n  1093→Drawings section.\n  1094→하드웨어 사양\n  1095→87\n  1096→\n  1097→\n  1098→=== 페이지 88 ===\n  1099→Set up the Screw-bit System\n  1100→1. Place the bit into the bit holder.\n  1101→2. Place the screw carrier on the bit holder.\n  1102→3. All screw carriers must be adjusted so that the screw head sits stable on the screw\n  1103→carrier avoiding a gap in between. This needs to be done to ensure high performance of\n  1104→the Screw-bit System.\n  1105→See the pictures below as reference.\n  1106→Appearance\n  1107→Adjustment method\n  1108→하드웨어 사양\n  1109→88\n  1110→\n  1111→\n  1112→=== 페이지 89 ===\n  1113→Appearance\n  1114→Adjustment method\n  1115→Din 912 / ISO\n  1116→4762 /\n  1117→ISO 14579 /\n  1118→ISO 14580 /\n  1119→ASME B18.3\n  1120→Hex Cylinder\n  1121→ISO 14581 /\n  1122→ASME\n  1123→B18.6 HEX\n  1124→Counter\n  1125→sunk /\n  1126→ASME\n  1127→B18.6.3\n  1128→Torx\n  1129→Counter\n  1130→sunk\n  1131→DIN 7985A /\n  1132→ASME B18.6.3\n  1133→Cross\n  1134→recessed\n  1135→Button head /\n  1136→ASME B18.6.3\n  1137→Torx Button\n  1138→head\n  1139→4. When this is achieved, remove the screw and push in the screw fix (only Din 912, ISO\n  1140→4762, ISO 14579, ISO 14580 and ASME B18.3 HEX Cylinder screw types).\n  1141→The final setup of the Screw-bit System with the screw in place should look like in the\n  1142→pictures below.\n  1143→하드웨어 사양\n  1144→89\n  1145→\n  1146→\n  1147→=== 페이지 90 ===\n  1148→Screw\n  1149→standard\n  1150→Din 912 /\n  1151→ISO 4762 /\n  1152→ISO 14579 /\n  1153→ISO 14580 /\n  1154→ASME\n  1155→B18.3 Hex\n  1156→Cylinder\n  1157→ISO\n  1158→14581 /\n  1159→ASME\n  1160→B18.6 HEX\n  1161→Counter\n  1162→sunk /\n  1163→ASME\n  1164→B18.6.3\n  1165→Torx\n  1166→Counter\n  1167→sunk\n  1168→DIN 7985A /\n  1169→ASME\n  1170→B18.6.3\n  1171→Cross\n  1172→recessed\n  1173→Button\n  1174→head /\n  1175→ASME\n  1176→B18.6.3 Torx\n  1177→Button head\n  1178→Screw-bit\n  1179→System\n  1180→appearance\n  1181→Attaching the Screw-bit System to the Screwdriver\n  1182→To attach the Screw-bit System to the Screwdriver, follow the instructions below.\n  1183→1. Move the shank to the highest possible\n  1184→value by using the user interface in the\n  1185→robot or in the Web Client.\n  1186→2. Detach the Screwdriver from the Quick\n  1187→Changer.\n  1188→하드웨어 사양\n  1189→90\n  1190→\n  1191→\n  1192→=== 페이지 91 ===\n  1193→3. Remove the lid.\n  1194→4. Place the hex shape of the bit holder\n  1195→inside of the end of the Screwdriver's\n  1196→shank. The system will be attached to the\n  1197→Screwdriver by a magnetic force.\n  1198→5. Ensure that the bit holder is perfectly\n  1199→attached by gently shaking it to make sure\n  1200→it is not loose.\n  1201→Detaching the Screw-bit System from the Screwdriver\n  1202→To remove the Screw-bit System from the Screwdriver's shank, follow the instructions below.\n  1203→1. Move the shank all the way out to the\n  1204→highest possible value by operating the\n  1205→user interface in the robot or in the Web\n  1206→Client.\n  1207→2. Use the provided key to grab the bit\n  1208→holder. While holding the key, move the\n  1209→shank inwards (to a lower value) by\n  1210→operating the user interface in the robot or\n  1211→in the Web Client.\n  1212→Overview of the Items Needed Depending on the Screw Type and Size\n  1213→In the following tables, an overview is shown of the items needed depending on the screw\n  1214→type and size. Based on what screw type and size you have, search for the screw standard\n  1215→and the thread size and find what kind of bit, screw fix, screw carrier and bit holder you will\n  1216→need.\n  1217→하드웨어 사양\n  1218→91\n  1219→\n  1220→\n  1221→=== 페이지 92 ===\n  1222→For more information, see the example.\n  1223→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Metric Screws\n  1224→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Metric Screws\n  1225→Head type\n  1226→Cylinder\n  1227→Counter sunk\n  1228→Button head\n  1229→Screw\n  1230→standard\n  1231→Thread Size\n  1232→Bit holder, bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n  1233→M1.6\n  1234→N/A\n  1235→N/A\n  1236→N/A\n  1237→N/A\n  1238→M2\n  1239→N/A\n  1240→하드웨어 사양\n  1241→92\n  1242→\n  1243→\n  1244→=== 페이지 93 ===\n  1245→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Metric Screws\n  1246→M2.5\n  1247→N/A\n  1248→M3\n  1249→M4\n  1250→M5\n  1251→M6\n  1252→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for US Standard Screws\n  1253→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for US Standard Screws\n  1254→Head type\n  1255→Cylinder\n  1256→Button head\n  1257→Counter sunk\n  1258→Screw\n  1259→standard\n  1260→HEX\n  1261→Cross recessed Torx\n  1262→HEX\n  1263→Torx\n  1264→Thread Size Bit holder, bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n  1265→하드웨어 사양\n  1266→93\n  1267→\n  1268→\n  1269→=== 페이지 94 ===\n  1270→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for US Standard Screws\n  1271→1# \n  1272→N/A\n  1273→N/A\n  1274→N/A\n  1275→N/A\n  1276→2# \n  1277→N/A\n  1278→4# \n  1279→6# \n  1280→8# \n  1281→10#\n  1282→하드웨어 사양\n  1283→94\n  1284→\n  1285→\n  1286→=== 페이지 95 ===\n  1287→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for US Standard Screws\n  1288→12#\n  1289→N/A\n  1290→N/A\n  1291→N/A\n  1292→1/4\"\n  1293→N/A\n  1294→N/A\n  1295→N/A\n  1296→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1297→Aluminium\n  1298→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1299→Aluminium 1/2\n  1300→Head type\n  1301→Pan head\n  1302→Flat round with\n  1303→flange\n  1304→Lens head\n  1305→Appearance\n  1306→Standard\n  1307→DIN 7981 C/ ISO\n  1308→7049\n  1309→DIN 7981 F/ ISO\n  1310→7049\n  1311→WN 5251\n  1312→DIN 7983 C\n  1313→Thread Size\n  1314→Bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n  1315→ST2.2 / 2.2 /\n  1316→KB22 / K22\n  1317→N/A\n  1318→하드웨어 사양\n  1319→95\n  1320→\n  1321→\n  1322→=== 페이지 96 ===\n  1323→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1324→Aluminium 1/2\n  1325→ST 2.9\n  1326→N/A\n  1327→3 / M3 / KB30 /\n  1328→K30\n  1329→N/A\n  1330→N/A\n  1331→N/A\n  1332→ST3.5.3 / 3.5 /\n  1333→KB35 / K35\n  1334→ST 3.9\n  1335→N/A\n  1336→N/A\n  1337→N/A\n  1338→4 / M4 / KB40 /\n  1339→K40\n  1340→N/A\n  1341→N/A\n  1342→N/A\n  1343→하드웨어 사양\n  1344→96\n  1345→\n  1346→\n  1347→=== 페이지 97 ===\n  1348→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1349→Aluminium 1/2\n  1350→ST 4.2\n  1351→N/A\n  1352→ST 4.8\n  1353→N/A\n  1354→N/A\n  1355→50 / M5 / KB50 /\n  1356→K50\n  1357→N/A\n  1358→N/A\n  1359→N/A\n  1360→ST 5.5\n  1361→N/A\n  1362→N/A\n  1363→N/A\n  1364→ST 6.3\n  1365→N/A\n  1366→N/A\n  1367→N/A\n  1368→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1369→Aluminium 2/2\n  1370→Head type\n  1371→Counter sunk\n  1372→하드웨어 사양\n  1373→97\n  1374→\n  1375→\n  1376→=== 페이지 98 ===\n  1377→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1378→Aluminium 2/2\n  1379→Appearance\n  1380→Standard\n  1381→DIN 7500 M\n  1382→DIN 14586 C\n  1383→DIN 7982 C\n  1384→Thread Size\n  1385→Bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n  1386→20 / M2 / K20\n  1387→N/A\n  1388→N/A\n  1389→ST2.2 / 2.2 / KB22 / K22\n  1390→N/A\n  1391→2.5 / M2.5 / KB25 / K25\n  1392→N/A\n  1393→N/A\n  1394→ST 2.9\n  1395→N/A\n  1396→하드웨어 사양\n  1397→98\n  1398→\n  1399→\n  1400→=== 페이지 99 ===\n  1401→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1402→Aluminium 2/2\n  1403→3 / M3 / KB30 / K30\n  1404→N/A\n  1405→N/A\n  1406→ST3.5.3 / 3.5 / KB35 /\n  1407→K35\n  1408→N/A\n  1409→ST 3.9\n  1410→N/A\n  1411→4 / M4 / KB40 / K40\n  1412→N/A\n  1413→N/A\n  1414→ST 4.2\n  1415→N/A\n  1416→하드웨어 사양\n  1417→99\n  1418→\n  1419→\n  1420→=== 페이지 100 ===\n  1421→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for\n  1422→Aluminium 2/2\n  1423→ST 4.8\n  1424→N/A\n  1425→50 / M5 / KB50 / K50\n  1426→N/A\n  1427→N/A\n  1428→ST 5.5\n  1429→N/A\n  1430→60 / M6\n  1431→N/A\n  1432→N/A\n  1433→ST 6.3\n  1434→N/A\n  1435→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n  1436→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n  1437→Head type\n  1438→Counter sunk\n  1439→Flat round with flange\n  1440→하드웨어 사양\n  1441→100\n  1442→\n  1443→\n  1444→=== 페이지 101 ===\n  1445→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n  1446→Appearance\n  1447→Standard\n  1448→ISO 4042\n  1449→WN 1411\n  1450→WN 5451\n  1451→Thread size and Bit holder/ Bit extender\n  1452→Bit, screw carrier and screw fix needed\n  1453→20 / M2 / K20\n  1454→N/A\n  1455→N/A\n  1456→ST2.2 / 2.2 / KB22 / K22\n  1457→N/A\n  1458→2.5 / M2.5 / KB25 / K25\n  1459→3 / M3 / KB30 / K30\n  1460→ST3.5.3 / 3.5 / KB35 / K35\n  1461→N/A\n  1462→하드웨어 사양\n  1463→101\n  1464→\n  1465→\n  1466→=== 페이지 102 ===\n  1467→Items Needed Depending on Screw Type and Size for Self-tapping Screws for Plastic\n  1468→4 / M4 / KB40 / K40\n  1469→50 / M5 / KB50 / K50\n  1470→N/A\n  1471→60 / M6\n  1472→N/A\n  1473→N/A\n  1474→Screwdriver Position to Execute Commands\n  1475→To successfully execute the Screwdriver commands, it is fundamental to position the\n  1476→Screwdriver correctly. This is achieved if the following two conditions are met:\n  1477→1. The Screw-bit System must be perfectly aligned to\n  1478→the screw or thread.\n  1479→하드웨어 사양\n  1480→102\n  1481→\n  1482→\n  1483→=== 페이지 103 ===\n  1484→2. The distance between the Screwdriver's bottom part\n  1485→and the surface where the action takes place must\n  1486→be within the range of 0-8 mm [0-0.31 inches].\n  1487→To successfully execute the Screwdriver commands, it is fundamental to operate the\n  1488→Screwdriver downwards or maximum sidewards. The Screwdriver should not be operated\n  1489→upwards or with an angle higher than 90° orientate with respect to the ground, since this will\n  1490→trigger the protective feature.\n  1491→LED - Device Status\n  1492→The screwdriver has a LED that shows the device status.\n  1493→하드웨어 사양\n  1494→103\n  1495→\n  1496→\n  1497→=== 페이지 104 ===\n  1498→Color\n  1499→Device Status\n  1500→ No light\n  1501→Power missing\n  1502→ Steady green\n  1503→Ready to work - Idle - Static\n  1504→ Blinking green\n  1505→Initializing\n  1506→ Steady orange\n  1507→Busy – Moving/rotating shank\n  1508→ Blinking orange\n  1509→Operational malfunction\n  1510→ Steady red\n  1511→Not working – Hardware problem\n  1512→ Blinking red\n  1513→Safety – Emergency stop\n  1514→Torque Angle Curve and Torque Gradient\n  1515→The torque gradient shows how the torque is applied in the last phase of the Tightening\n  1516→screw command. This could be used as an indicator to detect if a Tightening command is\n  1517→performed correctly.\n  1518→참고\n  1519→When using self-tapping screws, if the tapping torque is very close to the\n  1520→target torque, the torque gradient might provide an invalid value.\n  1521→For instance, the torque gradient could be different if:\n  1522→•\n  1523→The hole thread is not long enough\n  1524→•\n  1525→The hole thread is different from the screw thread\n  1526→•\n  1527→The hole thread is not clean (for instance by deburrs from CNC machining)\n  1528→•\n  1529→The friction between the screw thread and the hole thread is too low or too high\n  1530→•\n  1531→The friction between the screw head and the tighten part is too low or too high\n  1532→A torque gradient variable is made available to be checked in the robot program.\n  1533→The graph below shows a normal Torque/Angle curve. In this case has been made with an\n  1534→M4 screw and 2.4 Nm as target torque.\n  1535→하드웨어 사양\n  1536→104\n  1537→\n  1538→\n  1539→=== 페이지 105 ===\n  1540→Torque angle curve Metric\n  1541→Torque angle curve US Standard\n  1542→Adjusting the Bellow back in Place\n  1543→참고\n  1544→Initially, the bellow should not come out of place, but if it does, follow the\n  1545→instructions below to adjust it back in place.\n  1546→하드웨어 사양\n  1547→105\n  1548→\n  1549→\n  1550→"}]},"uuid":"6f910c31-98cb-4482-abfd-5fdcd54db332","timestamp":"2026-02-26T10:12:03.520Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"97dbffe9-9b10-4a08-b514-db2e591327a2"}
